# Logging & Observability

Don't enforce logging everywhere. Instead, notice when something would benefit from being observable and ask.

## When to Suggest

Use your judgment. Suggest logging to the user when you encounter:

- Operations that cross system boundaries (API calls, database queries, external services)
- Error handling paths — if something fails, future-you wants to know what and why
- State transitions that are hard to reproduce or debug (e.g., payment status changes, user role changes)
- Long-running or async operations where progress or completion matters
- Anything the user would say "I wish I had logged that" after a production incident

## How to Suggest

Don't add logging silently. Ask the user:

- "This calls an external service — would you like to log the request and response?"
- "This error is caught and translated — should we log the original error for debugging?"
- "This changes the order status — worth logging the transition?"

## If the User Says Yes

- Log at the appropriate level (debug for noise, info for events, warn/error for problems)
- Include enough context to be useful (what happened, to what, and any relevant IDs)
- Never log sensitive data — respect the security rule
